'Someone phoned me just before you arrived,
but they

747
00:52:27,730 --> 00:52:29,329
didn't leave a message.'

748
00:52:29,329 --> 00:52:32,329
'Go ahead,' said Belen.

749
00:52:32,329 --> 00:52:35,450
'I'll go into the kitchen.'

750
00:52:35,450 --> 00:52:40,099
'No, no problem,' answered Maggie.

751
00:52:40,099 --> 00:52:41,099
'Stay.

752
00:52:41,099 --> 00:52:42,780
I won't be a minute.

753
00:52:42,780 --> 00:52:45,579
Then we can eat.'

754
00:52:45,579 --> 00:52:48,829
Maggie rang the mobile number.

755
00:52:48,829 --> 00:52:51,859
'Hello,' said a foreign voice.

756
00:52:51,859 --> 00:52:53,240
It was a man.

757
00:52:53,240 --> 00:52:56,300
'Oh hello,' said Maggie.

758
00:52:56,300 --> 00:53:01,750
'You called this number earlier - Bath 726549.

759
00:53:01,750 --> 00:53:05,619
Who are you?'

760
00:53:05,619 --> 00:53:08,860
'I'm sorry,' answered the man.

761
00:53:08,860 --> 00:53:10,990
'It was a wrong number.'

762
00:53:10,990 --> 00:53:13,660
'Oh, OK.

763
00:53:13,660 --> 00:53:20,210
Bye then,' said Maggie and put the phone down.

764
00:53:20,210 --> 00:53:21,850
'Wrong number.'

765
00:53:21,850 --> 00:53:23,599
Maggie turned to Belen.

766
00:53:23,599 --> 00:53:28,280
'Someone with a Spanish-sounding voice, I
think.'

767
00:53:28,280 --> 00:53:32,170
'From Chile, perhaps?' asked Belen.

768
00:53:32,170 --> 00:53:34,500
'Maybe,' said Maggie.

769
00:53:34,500 --> 00:53:36,220
'Anyway, it's not important.

770
00:53:36,220 --> 00:53:41,119
Let's go into the kitchen and have dinner.'

771
00:53:41,119 --> 00:53:43,890
Maggie and Belen ate the lasagne.

772
00:53:43,890 --> 00:53:51,380
They looked at photos from their holiday and
laughed at some of the things they remembered.

773
00:53:51,380 --> 00:53:56,000
There was a noise from the living room and
they both jumped.

774
00:53:56,000 --> 00:53:57,930
'It's OK.'

775
00:53:57,930 --> 00:53:58,930
Maggie laughed.

776
00:53:58,930 --> 00:54:01,310
'It's only the window.

777
00:54:01,310 --> 00:54:04,640
When it's windy, it always makes a noise.'

778
00:54:04,640 --> 00:54:10,569
But then there was another, different noise.

779
00:54:10,569 --> 00:54:12,640
Someone was at the front door.

780
00:54:12,640 --> 00:54:18,480
'What a bad time to call,' said Maggie.

781
00:54:18,480 --> 00:54:21,230
She walked to the front door.

782
00:54:21,230 --> 00:54:25,049
When she opened it, she saw a man.

783
00:54:25,049 --> 00:54:26,049
'Yes?'

784
00:54:26,049 --> 00:54:27,980
she asked.

785
00:54:27,980 --> 00:54:29,920
'Can I help you?'

786
00:54:29,920 --> 00:54:36,450
'Are you Maggie Cox?' asked the man.

787
00:54:36,450 --> 00:54:39,260
'Yes,' answered Maggie.

788
00:54:39,260 --> 00:54:41,130
'And who...'

789
00:54:41,130 --> 00:54:44,130
But she didn't finish her question.

790
00:54:44,130 --> 00:54:49,300
The man came into the house and closed the
door behind him.

791
00:54:49,300 --> 00:54:53,730
'Excuse me!' said Maggie angrily.

792
00:54:53,730 --> 00:54:56,359
'What are you doing?

793
00:54:56,359 --> 00:54:57,710
Who are you?'

794
00:54:57,710 --> 00:55:01,720
Belen heard her shouting and came out of the
kitchen.

795
00:55:01,720 --> 00:55:08,160
'Sit down, both of you,' said the man quietly.

796
00:55:08,160 --> 00:55:13,400
'I don't want to hurt you.'

797
00:55:13,400 --> 00:55:18,549
Belen and Maggie sat together on the sofa.

798
00:55:18,549 --> 00:55:27,710
'I'm looking for a friend of yours - Xavier
Santos,' said the man.

799
00:55:27,710 --> 00:55:33,260
'He's not here,' said Maggie and Belen at
the same time.

800
00:55:33,260 --> 00:55:36,960
'Who are you?' asked Maggie.

801
00:55:36,960 --> 00:55:46,289
'Let's just say I'm a friend of the Santos
family,' answered the man.

802
00:55:46,289 --> 00:55:52,710
'I know he's in England, and I want to talk
to him.'

803
00:55:52,710 --> 00:55:59,990
'I haven't heard from him since we got back
from Chile,' said Maggie quickly.

804
00:55:59,990 --> 00:56:03,869
'Really?' said the man.

805
00:56:03,869 --> 00:56:11,190
He walked round the room and looked at everything
- postcards from friends on holiday, the phone

806
00:56:11,190 --> 00:56:14,660
bill that was on
top of the TV.

807
00:56:14,660 --> 00:56:21,549
Then Maggie remembered Xavier's email - it
was on the table next to her.

808
00:56:21,549 --> 00:56:25,589
It was too late to move it.

809
00:56:25,589 --> 00:56:27,839
The man saw it.

810
00:56:27,839 --> 00:56:33,630
'So this is from another Xavier, is it?

811
00:56:33,630 --> 00:56:40,339
Where's the letter he talks about in the email?'
asked the man.

812
00:56:40,339 --> 00:56:45,359
'I haven't had it yet,' said Maggie.

813
00:56:45,359 --> 00:56:50,240
She was afraid and she could feel Belen was
too.

814
00:56:50,240 --> 00:56:54,020
She didn't understand what the man was doing
in her

815
00:56:54,020 --> 00:56:55,020
house.

816
00:56:55,020 --> 00:57:00,550
'How did you know where I live?' asked Maggie.

817
00:57:00,550 --> 00:57:07,470
'I found your address in Xavier's home,' said
the man.

818
00:57:07,470 --> 00:57:09,700
'And your photo.

819
00:57:09,700 --> 00:57:16,059
Did you have a good time in my country, Maggie?'

820
00:57:16,059 --> 00:57:19,039
Maggie didn't answer the question.

821
00:57:19,039 --> 00:57:26,339
She asked, but half of her didn't want to
know, 'Why are you looking for Xavier?'

822
00:57:26,339 --> 00:57:32,690
'He's got something that I want,' said the
man.

823
00:57:32,690 --> 00:57:39,349
'But maybe he gave it to you to bring back
to England.'

824
00:57:39,349 --> 00:57:43,740
The man walked up to Maggie and
stood very close.

825
00:57:43,740 --> 00:57:49,460
'He didn't give me anything,' said Maggie.

826
00:57:49,460 --> 00:57:57,450
'Maybe he didn't, but I know that Xavier will
come here soon.

827
00:57:57,450 --> 00:58:01,760
And when he does, I'll be ready for him.'

828
00:58:01,760 --> 00:58:06,010
The man looked hard at Maggie.

829
00:58:06,010 --> 00:58:14,080
'You did a bad thing, Maggie, when you chose
Xavier,' said the man.

830
00:58:14,080 --> 00:58:18,770
'He's not right for a nice girl like you.'

831
00:58:18,770 --> 00:58:20,980
He moved away.

832
00:58:20,980 --> 00:58:27,790
'Remember, Maggie, I'll come back.'

833
00:58:27,790 --> 00:58:32,410
Belen and Maggie jumped up when the man left.

834
00:58:32,410 --> 00:58:37,390
'You must phone the police, Maggie,' said
Belen.

835
00:58:37,390 --> 00:58:39,250
'This is terrible.

836
00:58:39,250 --> 00:58:42,330
You must come home with
me.

837
00:58:42,330 --> 00:58:45,380
You're not safe here.'

838
00:58:45,380 --> 00:58:49,430
Maggie phoned and told the police everything.

839
00:58:49,430 --> 00:58:52,940
She told them, 'I'm not going to stay here.

840
00:58:52,940 --> 00:58:56,109
I'm going to stay with a friend tonight.

841
00:58:56,109 --> 00:59:06,730
You can
call me on my mobile, 04776 567831.'

842
00:59:06,730 --> 00:59:12,920
The police asked her to go to the police station
the next day.

843
00:59:12,920 --> 00:59:17,539
Maggie put some things in a bag, ready to
leave with Belen.

844
00:59:17,539 --> 00:59:22,140
'I'm so stupid,' said Maggie.

845
00:59:22,140 --> 00:59:26,000
'I thought Xavier was really nice.

846
00:59:26,000 --> 00:59:32,250
I believed he loved me, but he was just playing.'

847
00:59:32,250 --> 00:59:43,220
Maggie and Belen called a taxi and left Moreland
Road half an hour later.

848
00:59:43,220 --> 00:59:45,549
CHAPTER EIGHT

849
00:59:45,549 --> 00:59:47,869
What Sam didn't know

850
00:59:47,869 --> 00:59:53,270
'How am I going to find 700 pounds?'

851
00:59:53,270 --> 00:59:57,760
thought Sam that Friday evening.

852
00:59:57,760 --> 01:00:00,930
'And why didn't I tell Hannah about Jeremy?'

853
01:00:00,930 --> 01:00:04,150
But it was too late now.

854
01:00:04,150 --> 01:00:06,859
Emma was going to Norway.

855
01:00:06,859 --> 01:00:09,630
'That's so great, Dad!

856
01:00:09,630 --> 01:00:12,549
Thank you,' she said and kissed him.

857
01:00:12,549 --> 01:00:16,960
It made Sam happy to see
her so excited.

858
01:00:16,960 --> 01:00:22,140
'I know what I'll do,' thought Sam sadly.

859
01:00:22,140 --> 01:00:29,589
'On Monday morning I'll take some of the jewellery
my mother gave me before she died.

860
01:00:29,589 --> 01:00:32,650
There's a
jeweller's shop on the way to work.

861
01:00:32,650 --> 01:00:38,190
I'm sure they'll be interested in buying diamond
rings.'

862
01:00:38,190 --> 01:00:40,430
Sam didn't want to sell the jewellery.

863
01:00:40,430 --> 01:00:45,349
He knew his mother wanted Emma to have it.

864
01:00:45,349 --> 01:00:48,930
'Maybe my brother is right,' he thought.

865
01:00:48,930 --> 01:00:52,770
'I do need a job with better money.

866
01:00:52,770 --> 01:01:00,069
I don't know how much longer we can go on
like this.'

867
01:01:00,069 --> 01:01:07,770
That Friday morning, six hundred kilometres
away in the city of Edinburgh, something important

868
01:01:07,770 --> 01:01:10,960
happened that could change Sam's life.

869
01:01:10,960 --> 01:01:14,849
But
Sam knew nothing about it.

870
01:01:14,849 --> 01:01:23,680
Two people, a man and a woman, arrived at
the offices of lawyers Barrett, Grabbe and

871
01:01:23,680 --> 01:01:25,910
Lennox.

872
01:01:25,910 --> 01:01:31,290
A man took the two visitors upstairs to the
office of Frank Barrett.

873
01:01:31,290 --> 01:01:37,680
It was a very old-fashioned place with big,
dark wood furniture.

874
01:01:37,680 --> 01:01:41,800
There were hundreds of law books all around
the room.

875
01:01:41,800 --> 01:01:47,510
'Good morning,' said Mr Barrett to the visitors.

876
01:01:47,510 --> 01:01:51,950
'It's Paul and Sonia Cooper, isn't it?

877
01:01:51,950 --> 01:01:53,859
Please sit down.'

878
01:01:53,859 --> 01:02:00,160
'Thank you,' said Sonia and sat down next
to her brother, Paul.

879
01:02:00,160 --> 01:02:03,760
'I'm sorry about your father,' said Mr Barrett.

880
01:02:03,760 --> 01:02:07,690
'We looked after his business for years here.'

881
01:02:07,690 --> 01:02:11,060
'Thank you,' said Paul.

882
01:02:11,060 --> 01:02:14,810
'He was ninety-one when he died.

883
01:02:14,810 --> 01:02:20,049
But now we need to know what he decided to
do with his money and things.'

884
01:02:20,049 --> 01:02:22,869
'Paul!' said Sonia.

885
01:02:22,869 --> 01:02:25,700
'That sounds terrible!'

886
01:02:25,700 --> 01:02:28,849
'It's OK,' said Mr Barrett.

887
01:02:28,849 --> 01:02:34,059
'Let me tell you what he wrote in his will.'

888
01:02:34,059 --> 01:02:39,500
Mr Barrett didn't always enjoy reading a will
to a family.

889
01:02:39,500 --> 01:02:43,059
Sometimes there were surprises in it that
they didn't like.

890
01:02:43,059 --> 01:02:53,210
'I leave my house and all that is in the house
to my two children, Paul and Sonia.

891
01:02:53,210 --> 01:02:59,200
My money I give to my grandchildren, Robert,
Amy and

892
01:02:59,200 --> 01:03:00,200
Charlie.'

893
01:03:00,200 --> 01:03:04,740
Paul and Sonia looked pleased.

894
01:03:04,740 --> 01:03:08,950
He continued, 'But not all of it.'

895
01:03:08,950 --> 01:03:12,619
Their smiles became smaller.

896
01:03:12,619 --> 01:03:22,049
'I want to leave some of my money to a special
person who was a good friend to me in my life

897
01:03:22,049 --> 01:03:24,579
- Samuel Davies.

898
01:03:24,579 --> 01:03:33,210
'About thirty years ago, when my wife died,
Sam lived next door to me.

899
01:03:33,210 --> 01:03:39,130
He was a young man, but he spent many hours
with me at that time.

900
01:03:39,130 --> 01:03:45,410
He visited me most days and listened to me
when I talked about my wife.

901
01:03:45,410 --> 01:03:47,200
He was a true friend.

902
01:03:47,200 --> 01:03:51,549
I have never forgotten how kind he was.

903
01:03:51,549 --> 01:04:00,030
I want to say thank you to him and to give
him 50,000 pounds.'

904
01:04:00,030 --> 01:04:06,850
A few minutes later, Mr Barrett finished reading
and the office was quiet.

905
01:04:06,850 --> 01:04:14,020
Then Paul Cooper said, 'Samuel Davies is a
lucky man - 50,000

906
01:04:14,020 --> 01:04:21,220
pounds is a lot of money, just for talking
to Dad.'

907
01:04:21,220 --> 01:04:25,050
And Sonia said, 'I don't remember him.

908
01:04:25,050 --> 01:04:32,849
Well, that's what Dad wanted to do, and it's
his money, so that's that.

909
01:04:32,849 --> 01:04:35,310
We can't change anything.

910
01:04:35,310 --> 01:04:41,190
But how much will there be for the grandchildren
- Paul's children?'

911
01:04:41,190 --> 01:04:43,339
'I'm not sure yet.

912
01:04:43,339 --> 01:04:47,520
We'll have to wait and see,' said Mr Barrett.

913
01:04:47,520 --> 01:04:50,859
'We have to let Samuel Davies know.

914
01:04:50,859 --> 01:04:57,849
It could take quite a long time - you
know, the address your father gave us could

915
01:04:57,849 --> 01:04:59,760
be wrong now.

916
01:04:59,760 --> 01:05:02,930
But I'll write to you as soon as I know.'

917
01:05:02,930 --> 01:05:09,700
'But if you don't find him, what happens to
the money?' asked Sonia.

918
01:05:09,700 --> 01:05:12,770
'Oh, I'm sure we'll find him.

919
01:05:12,770 --> 01:05:21,549
It could take months, but we usually find
people in the end,' replied Mr Barrett.

920
01:05:21,549 --> 01:05:25,890
Paul and Sonia left the lawyer's office quietly.

921
01:05:25,890 --> 01:05:32,950
Mr Barrett gave some papers to his secretary
and she wrote a letter to Samuel Davies.

922
01:05:32,950 --> 01:05:37,380
At
lunchtime she took the letter to the post

923
01:05:37,380 --> 01:05:38,440
office.

924
01:05:38,440 --> 01:05:45,170
As she put it in the post box, she thought,
'Lucky Samuel Davies.

925
01:05:45,170 --> 01:05:50,210
What's he going to do with 50,000 pounds?'

926
01:05:50,210 --> 01:06:01,940
Back in Bath that Friday evening, of course
Sam had no idea about Mr Cooper and his money.

927
01:06:01,940 --> 01:06:04,069
He went to bed unhappy.

928
01:06:04,069 --> 01:06:08,770
Was it right to sell
his mother's jewellery?

929
01:06:08,770 --> 01:06:18,500
And what job could a man his age get that
paid more money?

930
01:06:18,500 --> 01:06:19,500
CHAPTER NINE

931
01:06:19,500 --> 01:06:21,870
Fire!

932
01:06:21,870 --> 01:06:33,039
At three-thirty on the morning of Saturday
15th March, a small fire started in a van

933
01:06:33,039 --> 01:06:37,079
at the back of the mail depot in Bath.

934
01:06:37,079 --> 01:06:42,839
Nobody saw it
at first because everyone was inside the building.

935
01:06:42,839 --> 01:06:49,270
Then someone smelled something and shouted,
'Fire!'

936
01:06:49,270 --> 01:06:53,760
Another person ran outside and saw what was
happening.

937
01:06:53,760 --> 01:06:56,570
Someone else phoned the fire
service.

938
01:06:56,570 --> 01:07:02,319
They tried to put out the fire, but they couldn't.

939
01:07:02,319 --> 01:07:07,260
The fire service arrived very quickly and
put out the fire.

940
01:07:07,260 --> 01:07:12,140
But two big bags of letters were lost.

941
01:07:12,140 --> 01:07:21,579
In those bags were four very important
letters for some people in Moreland Road.

